Rey Diaz lived underground not out of any concern for security, but because of his heliophobia. The claustrophobic environment, far removed from the sunshine, made him feel a little more comfortable. He watched the live broadcast of the Mercury test from the basement where he lived. It wasn\u8217?t actually live, since the images took about seven minutes to reach Earth. When the blast on Mercury had concluded and the rock rain was still falling in the post-fireball darkness, he received a telephone call from the rotating chair of the PDC, who said that the tremendous power of the stellar hydrogen bombs had made a deep impression on the PDC leadership, and that the permanent member states had requested that the next Wallfacer hearing be held as soon as possible to discuss the bombs\u8217? manufacture and deployment. The chair said that although the number of bombs Rey Diaz had requested was an impossibility, the major powers were indeed interested in the production of this weapon.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
Over ten hours after the conclusion of the Mercury test, as he was watching Mercury\u8217?s new ring sparkling on the television, a guard\u8217?s voice came over the intercom to tell him that his psychiatrist had arrived for an appointment.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?I never asked for any psychiatrist. Send him away!\u8221? He felt exasperated, like he had suffered some great indignity.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Don\u8217?t be like that, Mr. Rey Diaz,\u8221? said another, calmer voice, evidently the visitor\u8217?s. \u8220?I can let you see the sun\u8230?\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Get the hell out,\u8221? he shouted, but then immediately changed his mind. \u8220?No. Seize that idiot and find out where he came from.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?\u8230? because I know the cause of your condition,\u8221? the voice continued, still calm. \u8220?Mr. Rey Diaz, please believe me. You and I are the only ones in the world who know.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
At this, Rey Diaz suddenly grew alert, and said, \u8220?Let him in.\u8221? He stared at the ceiling for a few seconds through haggard eyes, then got up slowly and picked up a tie from the cluttered sofa, only to toss it back again. He walked over to the mirror, straightened his collar, and combed his hair with his hands, like he was preparing for a solemn event.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
He knew that it was indeed a solemn event.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
The visitor was a handsome middle-aged man who walked in but did not introduce himself. He frowned slightly at the room\u8217?s heavy odor of cigars and alcohol, then simply stood there calmly as Rey Diaz looked him over.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Why do I have the feeling I\u8217?ve seen you before?\u8221? he said, as he looked at the visitor.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?That\u8217?s not strange, Mr. Rey Diaz. Everyone says I look like Superman, from the old movies.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Do you really believe you\u8217?re Superman?\u8221? Rey Diaz said. He sat down on the sofa, picked up a cigar, bit off the end, and began to light it.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?That question shows that you already know what kind of man I am. I\u8217?m not Superman, Mr. Rey Diaz. Nor are you.\u8221? As he spoke, the younger man took a step forward. Rey Diaz found that the man was standing directly in front of him, peering down at him through the cloud of smoke he had just exhaled. So he stood up.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
The visitor said, \u8220?Wallfacer Manuel Rey Diaz, I am your Wallbreaker.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
Gloomily, Rey Diaz nodded.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?May I sit down?\u8221? the Wallbreaker asked.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?You may not,\u8221? Rey Diaz said, slowly blowing smoke in the other man\u8217?s face.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Don\u8217?t be depressed,\u8221? the Wallbreaker said with a considerate smile.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?I\u8217?m not,\u8221? Rey Diaz said, his voice cold and hard like stone.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
The Wallbreaker walked over to the wall and flipped a switch. Somewhere, ventilator fans started humming.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Don\u8217?t mess with things around here,\u8221? Rey Diaz warned.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?You need a little fresh air. And, more than that, you need sun. I\u8217?m quite familiar with this room, Wallfacer Rey Diaz. In the images sent by the sophons I have often watched you pace back and forth like a caged beast. No one in the world has stared at you for as long as I have, and on those days, believe me, it wasn\u8217?t any easier for me.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
The Wallbreaker looked straight at Rey Diaz, whose expression was as blank as an ice sculpture, and then he went on. \u8220?Compared to Frederick Tyler, you are a brilliant strategist. A competent Wallfacer. Please trust that this is not flattery. I must admit that for quite some time, for nearly a decade, you had me fooled. Your mania for the superbomb, such an inefficient weapon in a space battle, successfully concealed your own strategic direction, and for a long while I couldn\u8217?t find any clue to crack your true strategy. I struggled in the maze that you laid down, and at one point almost despaired.\u8221? The Wallbreaker looked up at the ceiling, overcome by the memory of those difficult times. \u8220?Later, I thought of checking out information from before you became a Wallbreaker, but this wasn\u8217?t easy, because the sophons were unable to help. You know, in those days, only a limited number of sophons had reached Earth, and as a South American head of state you had not attracted their attention. So I had to resort to conventional means to gather materials. This took three years. In those materials, one man stood out: William Cosmo. You met him in secret on three occasions. The sophons did not record the content of your conversations, so I will never know, but for the head of a small, undeveloped country to meet three times with a Western astrophysicist is highly unusual. We now know that at that time you had already been preparing to become a Wallfacer.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?No doubt what interested you was the fruit of Dr. Cosmo\u8217?s research. How those results first came to your attention I am not clear on at this time, but you had a background in engineering, and you had the successful experience of your socialism-loving predecessor, who had equal enthusiasm for a nation ruled by engineers. This was a major reason why you became his successor. So you ought to have had the capability and sensitivity to notice the potential significance of Cosmo\u8217?s research.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Once the Trisolar Crisis began, Dr. Cosmo\u8217?s research team worked on studying the atmosphere of the Trisolaran stellar system. They speculated that the atmosphere had been produced by a former planet that had collided with a star. As it collided, it broke apart the outer layers, its photosphere and troposphere, causing the stellar matter inside to be ejected into space and form a surrounding atmosphere. Due to the total irregularity of the system\u8217?s motion, there are times when the stars pass each other quite closely, and at those times, one star\u8217?s atmosphere is dispersed by the gravity of the other star, only to be replenished by eruptions on the stellar surface. These aren\u8217?t constant eruptions, more like volcanoes that experience sudden outbreaks. This is the reason for the continual contraction and expansion of the stars\u8217? atmosphere. To prove this hypothesis, Cosmo searched the universe to find another star with an atmosphere that was ejected following a collision with a planet. In the third year of the Crisis Era, he succeeded.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Dr. Cosmo\u8217?s team discovered planetary system 275E1, about eighty-four light-years from the Solar System. Hubble II had not gone into operation at that time, so they used the wobble method. By observing and calculating the wobble frequency and light mask, they learned that the planet was quite close to its parent star. At first, this discovery did not attract too much attention because the astronomy community had by then discovered more than two hundred planetary systems, but further observations revealed a shocking fact: The distance between planet and star was continually shrinking, and the rate of shrinkage was accelerating. This meant that humanity would, for the first time, observe a planet falling into a star. One year later\u8212?or, rather, eighty-four years prior to observation\u8212?it happened. Observational conditions at the time meant that the collision could only be determined based on the gravitational wobble and the periodic light mask. But then something wondrous happened: A spiral of matter appeared around the star, and this spiral flow continued to expand. It looked like a mainspring slowly unwinding with the star as its center. Cosmo and his colleagues realized that the material flow had been ejected from the planet\u8217?s crash point. The chunk of rock had crashed through the shell of that distant sun and ejected its stellar matter into space, where, due to the star\u8217?s own rotation, it formed a spiral.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?There were several key pieces of data here, sir. The star is a yellow G2 class with an absolute magnitude of 4.3 and a diameter of 1.2 million kilometers. Quite similar to our sun. The planet was about four percent of the mass of Earth, or a little smaller than Mercury, and the spiral cloud of material produced from the collision had a radius of up to three AU, more than the distance between our sun and the asteroid belt.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?And it was in this discovery that I found the crack with which to break open your real strategic plan. Now, as your Wallbreaker, I will explain your grand strategy.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Supposing that you are ultimately able to obtain those million or more stellar hydrogen bombs, you will, as you promised to the PDC, stockpile them all on Mercury. If the bombs are detonated in the rock of Mercury, they\u8217?ll be like a turbo-engine decelerating the planet. Eventually its speed will no longer be able to keep it in low orbit and it will fall into the sun. Next, what happened on 275E1 eighty-four light-years away is reenacted here: Mercury punctures the sun\u8217?s convective shell and ejects a huge amount of stellar matter from its radiation layer into space at high speed; which, as the sun rotates, forms a spiral atmosphere similar to that in 275E1. The sun differs from the Trisolaran system in that, as a lone star, it will never cross paths with another star, and therefore its atmosphere will continue to increase uninhibited until it becomes even thicker than the atmosphere of those stars. This was also confirmed by observations of 275E1. When the spiral flow of ejected matter expands outward from the sun like an unwound mainspring, its thickness eventually passes Mars\u8217?s orbit, at which point a magnificent chain reaction begins.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?First, three terrestrial planets\u8212?Venus, Earth, and Mars\u8212?pass through the sun\u8217?s spiraling atmosphere, losing speed due to the atmospheric friction and turning into three giant meteors that eventually crash into the sun. But well before this happens, the Earth\u8217?s atmosphere is stripped away by the intense friction of the solar matter. The oceans evaporate, and the lost atmosphere and evaporated oceans turn the Earth into a giant comet whose tail extends along its orbit to wrap all the way around the sun. The surface of the Earth returns to the fiery magma sea of its birth, where no life can survive.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?When Venus, Earth, and Mars crash into the sun, it exacerbates the sun\u8217?s ejection of solar matter into space. The single spiral flow of matter increases to four flows. Because the total mass of those three planets is forty times that of Mercury, and because their higher orbits mean they impact the sun at a much higher speed, each new spiral is ejected with a ferocity tens of times greater than Mercury\u8217?s. The existing spiral atmosphere rapidly expands until its edge approaches the orbit of Jupiter.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Friction produces only a very small deceleration effect on the huge mass of Jupiter, so it is quite some time before the spiral has a noticeable effect on Jupiter\u8217?s orbit. But Jupiter\u8217?s satellites meet one of the following two fates: friction strips them away from Jupiter and they lose speed and fall into the sun, or they lose speed in Jovian orbit and fall into the liquid planet.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?As the chain reaction continues, the decrease in speed from the spiral atmosphere, though small, is still present, and Jupiter\u8217?s orbit gradually decays. This causes it to pass through an increasingly dense atmosphere whose friction accelerates its loss in speed, thereby causing the orbit to decay even more quickly.\u8230? In this way, Jupiter eventually falls into the sun, too. Its mass is six hundred times that of the previous four planets, and the impact that such a massive body makes on the sun will, even according to the most conservative reasoning, produce an even more violent ejection of stellar matter, increasing the density of the spiral atmosphere and exacerbating the bitter cold of Uranus and Neptune. But another possibility is more likely: The fall of the Jovian giant pushes the edge of the spiral atmosphere out to the orbit of Uranus or even Neptune, and though the atmosphere is quite thin at the top, friction\u8217?s decelerating effects pull these two planets and their satellites toward the sun, too. What state the sun will be in and how the Solar System will have been transformed after the chain reaction finishes and the four dense terrestrial planets and four gas giants are consumed is unknowable. But one thing is certain: For life and for civilization, this will be a hell even crueler than attack by Trisolaris.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?As for Trisolaris, the Solar System is their only hope before their planet is engulfed by their stars. There is no other world they can migrate to in time, and therefore, their civilization will follow humanity into total destruction.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?This is your strategy: death for both sides. Once everything is prepared, with all of the stellar hydrogen bombs in place on Mercury, you will use it to coerce Trisolaris to surrender and gain the ultimate victory for humanity.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?What I\u8217?ve just presented is the outcome of the years of work that I, your Wallbreaker, have performed. I am not seeking your opinion or critique, because I know that all of this is true.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
As the Wallbreaker spoke, Rey Diaz had been listening quietly. The cigar in his hand was more than halfway gone, and he now turned it about as if appreciating the glow of the tip.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
The Wallbreaker sat down on the sofa, close beside him. Like a teacher evaluating a student\u8217?s homework, he continued unfatigued: \u8220?Mr. Rey Diaz, I said you are a brilliant strategist, or at least you demonstrated many excellent qualities in the formulation and implementation of this plan.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?For one thing, you took advantage of your own background. Right now, people clearly remember the humiliations you and your country suffered when the Orinoco nuclear facility was forced to be taken down as you were developing nuclear energy. The whole world saw your gloomy face, and you took advantage of outside perceptions of your paranoia about nuclear weapons to reduce or even eliminate any possible suspicion.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?But every detail in the execution of your plan demonstrates your talent as well. I will mention but one example: During the Mercury test, you wanted the rock to be blasted into the sky, but you insisted on excavating an ultra-deep shaft in a farsighted gambit. You quite precisely understood the tolerance of the PDC\u8217?s permanent member states for the cost of this enormous undertaking, and that is admirable.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?But you had one major slipup. Why did the first test have to be carried out on Mercury? There would have been plenty of time to bring the bombs there in a later phase, but maybe you got impatient and wanted to see the outcome of a stellar hydrogen bomb blast there. You saw it: lots of rock matter blasted to escape velocity, perhaps even exceeding your expectations. You were satisfied. But this provided the final confirmation of my hypothesis.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Yes, Mr. Rey Diaz, even given all my previous work, without that final event I might never have been able to determine your true strategic intentions. The notion was too mad. But it was grand, and even beautiful. If the chain reaction triggered by Mercury\u8217?s fall actually took place, then it would be the most magnificent movement of the entire symphony of the Solar System\~\u8230? although, unfortunately, humanity would only be able to enjoy the first section. Mr. Rey Diaz, you are a Wallfacer with the makings of a god. It is my honor to become your Wallbreaker.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
The Wallbreaker stood up and offered Rey Diaz a genial bow.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
Rey Diaz did not look at him. He took a puff of his cigar and blew out the smoke as he continued to examine it. \u8220?Fine. Then I\u8217?ll ask the question that Tyler asked.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
The Wallbreaker asked the question for him. \u8220?If what I say is true, then so what?\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
Rey Diaz stared at the lit end of the cigar and nodded.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?My answer is the same as Tyler\u8217?s Wallbreaker\u8217?s: The Lord does not care.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
Rey Diaz lifted his eyes from the cigar and looked questioningly at his Wallbreaker.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?You look crude, but your mind is sharp. Yet in the depths of your soul, you\u8217?re still crude. Your nature is that of a crude man. And this crudeness is revealed in the basis of this strategic plan. It\u8217?s greedy. Humanity doesn\u8217?t have the ability to manufacture so many stellar hydrogen bombs. Even if all of Earth\u8217?s industrial resources were exhausted, it wouldn\u8217?t produce even one-tenth of that number. And a million stellar hydrogen bombs is far from enough to decelerate Mercury into the sun. With a soldier\u8217?s recklessness, you formulated this impossible plan, and then stubbornly carried it forward step by step with the wily calculations of a superior strategist. Wallfacer Rey Diaz, this is truly a tragedy.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
As Rey Diaz looked at the Wallbreaker, his expression gradually filled with an elusive softness, and hints of convulsions showed on his coarsely lined face, gradually taking shape, until at last his suppressed laughter erupted.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Ha ha ha ha ha\u8230?\u8221? he laughed, pointing at the Wallbreaker. \u8220?Superman! Ha ha ha ha. I remember now. That\~\u8230? that old Superman. He could fly, and he could reverse the rotation of the Earth, but when he was riding a horse\~\u8230? ha ha ha ha\~\u8230? when he was riding a horse, he fell and broke his neck\~\u8230? ah ha ha ha\u8230?\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?It was Christopher Reeve, the actor who played Superman, who fell and broke his neck,\u8221? the Wallbreaker corrected him, quietly.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Do you imagine\~\u8230? imagine that your fate will be better than his? Ha ha ha ha\u8230?\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Since coming here, I have no regard for my fate. I\u8217?ve lived a full life,\u8221? the Wallbreaker said evenly. \u8220?But you, Mr. Rey Diaz, ought to think about your own fate.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?You\u8217?ll die first,\u8221? Rey Diaz said, smiling with his entire face as he pressed the cigar end directly between the Wallbreaker\u8217?s eyes. Then, when the Wallbreaker was covering his face with his hands, Rey Diaz took up a military-issue belt from the sofa, wrapped it around the Wallbreaker\u8217?s neck, and strangled him with every ounce of his strength. Although the Wallbreaker was young, he had no way to defend himself against Rey Diaz\u8217?s agile strength, and was thrown to the floor by his neck. Rey Diaz bellowed, \u8220?I\u8217?ll wring your neck! You bastard! Who sent you here to play smart? Who the hell are you? Bastard! I\u8217?ll wring your neck!\u8221? He tightened the belt and slammed the Wallbreaker\u8217?s head into the ground repeatedly, to the crunch of teeth smacking into the floor. When the guards burst in to separate them, the Wallbreaker\u8217?s face was purple, he was foaming at the mouth, and his eyes were protruding like a goldfish\u8217?s.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
Rey Diaz, still in a fury, struggled with the guards as he continued to shout, \u8220?Wring his neck! String him up and hang him! Right now! This is part of the plan! Do you fucking hear me? Part of the plan!\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
But the three guards did not carry out his order. One of them held Rey Diaz tightly while the other two lifted up the Wallbreaker, who had recovered his breath somewhat, and started to carry him out.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Just wait, you bastard. You won\u8217?t die easy,\u8221? he said, abandoning his efforts to escape the guard and have another go at the Wallbreaker. He let out a long sigh.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
The Wallbreaker looked back over the guard\u8217?s shoulder, a smile on his bruised and swollen face. He opened up a mouth that was missing several teeth and said, \u8220?I\u8217?ve lived a full life.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
