\u8220?Everyone can understand, Da Shi. The truth is simple. It\u8217?s the kind of thing that, once you hear it, you\u8217?ll wonder why you didn\u8217?t come up with it yourself. Do you know about mathematical axioms?\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?I took geometry in high school. \u8216?Only one straight line can be drawn between two points.\u8217? That kind of thing.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Right. So now we\u8217?re going to set out two axioms for cosmic civilization. First, survival is the primary need of civilization. Second, civilization continuously grows and expands, but the total matter in the universe remains constant.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?And then?\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?That\u8217?s it.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?What can you derive from those little things?\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?The same way you can figure out an entire case from a bullet or a drop of blood, cosmic sociology is able to describe a complete picture of galactic and cosmic civilization from those two axioms. That\u8217?s what science is like, Da Shi. The cornerstone of every discipline is quite simple.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?So let\u8217?s see you derive something.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?First, let\u8217?s talk about the Battle of Darkness. Would you believe me if I said that Starship Earth was a microcosm of cosmic civilization?\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?No. Starship Earth lacked resources like parts and fuel, but the universe doesn\u8217?t. It\u8217?s too big.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?You\u8217?re wrong. The universe is big, but life is bigger! That\u8217?s what the second axiom means. The amount of matter in the universe remains constant, but life grows exponentially. Exponentials are the devils of mathematics. If there\u8217?s a microscopic bacterium in the ocean that divides once every half hour, its descendants will fill the entire ocean in the space of a few days, so long as there are sufficient nutrients. Don\u8217?t let humanity and Trisolaris give you a false impression. These two civilizations are tiny, but they are only in their infancy. Once a civilization passes a certain technological threshold, the expansion of life through the universe is frightening. For instance, take humanity\u8217?s present navigation speed. In a million years, Earth civilization could fill the galaxy. And a million years is a short time measured against the universe.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?So you\u8217?re saying that, taking the long view, the entire universe might have that kind of\~\u8230? what are they calling it, a \u8216?dead hand\u8217??\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?No need for the long view. Right now the entire universe has been dealt that dead hand. Like Hines said, civilization may have started in the universe billions of years ago. Looking at the signs, the universe might be packed full already. Who knows how much empty space there is in the Milky Way or the universe, or how many resources are left?\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?But that\u8217?s not right, is it? The universe looks empty. We haven\u8217?t seen any other alien life apart from Trisolaris, right?\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?That\u8217?s what we\u8217?ll talk about next. Give me a cigarette.\u8221? Luo Ji groped about in the dark for a while before taking the cigarette from Shi Qiang\u8217?s hand. When Luo Ji next spoke, Shi Qiang realized he had moved to a spot three or four meters away. \u8220?We need to increase the distance to make it feel more like outer space,\u8221? Luo Ji said. Then he lit the cigarette by twisting its filter, and Shi Qiang lit one of his own. In the dark, two tiny red planets stood in distant opposition.\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Okay. To illustrate the problem, we now need to establish the most elementary model of cosmic civilization. These two balls of flame represent two civilized planets. The universe is made up of only these two planets, and apart from them there\u8217?s nothing else. Erase all of our surroundings. Can you locate that feeling?\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Yeah. That\u8217?s an easy feeling to find in a dark place like this.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Let\u8217?s call these two civilized worlds your civilization and my civilization. They\u8217?re separated by a great distance, say, a hundred light-years. You can detect that I exist, but you don\u8217?t know any details. However, I\u8217?m completely ignorant of your presence.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Right.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Now we need to define two concepts, \u8216?benevolence\u8217? and \u8216?malice\u8217? between civilizations. These words themselves aren\u8217?t very rigorous in a scientific context, so we\u8217?ve got to restrict their meaning. \u8216?Benevolence\u8217? means not taking the initiative to attack and eradicate other civilizations. \u8216?Malice\u8217? is the opposite.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?That\u8217?s a low bar for benevolence.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Next, consider your options for dealing with me. Please remember that the axioms of cosmic civilization should be kept in mind throughout the process, as well as the distance scale and the environment of space.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?I could choose to communicate with you.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?If you do that, you should be aware of the price you\u8217?ll pay: You\u8217?ll have exposed your existence to me.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Right. In the universe, that\u8217?s no small thing.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?There are different degrees of exposure. The strongest form of exposure is when I know your precise interstellar coordinates. Next is when I know your general direction, and the weakest is when I only know of your existence. But even the weakest form of exposure makes it possible for me to search for you, because since you\u8217?ve detected my existence, I know that I\u8217?ll be able to find you. It\u8217?s only a matter of time, from the standpoint of technological development.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?But my boy, I could still take the risk to talk to you. If you\u8217?re malicious, then it\u8217?s my bad luck. But if you\u8217?re benevolent, then we could have further exchanges and ultimately be united into a benevolent civilization.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Okay, Da Shi. Now we\u8217?ve come to the crux of it. Let\u8217?s return to the axioms of cosmic civilization: Even if I\u8217?m a benevolent civilization, can I determine at the start of our communication whether or not you are also benevolent?\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
\u8220?Of course not. That would violate the first axiom.\u8221?\par\pard\plain\hyphpar}{	
